SIMPLE: monition
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Monition
<hw>Mo*ni"tion</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F., fr. L.
<ets>monitio</ets>, from <ets>monere</ets> to warn, bring to mind; akin
to E. <ets>mind</ets>. See <er>Mind</er>, and cf. <er>Admonish</er>,
<er>Money</er>, <er>Monster</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Instruction or
advice given by way of caution; an admonition; a warning; a
caution.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Sage <qex>monitions</qex> from his friends.</q>
<rj><qau>Swift.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Information; indication; notice; advice.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>We have no visible <qex>monition</qex> of . . . other periods,
such as we have of the day by successive light and darkness.</q>
<rj><qau>Holder.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <fld>(Admiralty Practice)</fld> <def>A process in the
nature of a summons to appear and answer.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <fld>(Eccl. Law)</fld> <def>An order monishing a party
complained against to obey under pain of the law.</def>
<rj><au>Shipley.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Monitive</ent>⟦br⟧
